Q6. Session title (working titles accepted)Putting a Price Tag on the Invisible: Using Alternative Data to Value the UK's Intangible Assets(Alternative: Measuring the Unmeasurable: The Data Story Behind 62.3 Million UK Job Adverts)Q7. Formata - presentation with questions and answersQ8. Abstract (250 words maximum)In modern economics, "Data" is one of the most valuable assets a company owns. However, traditional National Accounts struggle to value intangible assets. You cannot look at a corporate balance sheet and see the monetary value of a bespoke internal database.To solve this macroeconomic blind spot, we rely on a "Sum-of-Costs" approach: valuing data based on the cost of the human labour required to build it. But how do you find the hidden data workforce when technical data processing tasks are now demanded across almost every occupation?This session tells the data story of how we bypassed lagging surveys and went straight to the labour market. We ingested 62.3 million raw UK job advertisements spanning five years and built a PySpark Natural Language Processing (NLP) pipeline to mathematically extract the UK’s true data workforce.We will walk through the rigorous AI filtration engine we engineered—including a calibrated 0.35 semantic vector threshold, a 10.0x Relative Share statistical multiplier, and our Probabilistic Crosswalk Matrix used to map Occupational codes (SOC) into Industry sectors (SIC).Attendees will see exactly how we transformed billions of unstructured, raw text phrases into a National Accounts-ready valuation framework, ultimately calculating the absolute macroeconomic investment the UK makes in "own-account" data capital.Q9. How your session relates to the theme - Data storytelling: what statistics can tell usThis session is fundamentally about using data to tell an economic story that is currently invisible to traditional statistical methods.We know the UK is undergoing a massive digital transformation, but our traditional National Accounts cannot fully "see" or value the internal data assets being created. Our session demonstrates how we can use alternative, unstructured data (62.3 million job adverts) to tell that story objectively.We will show how statistics—specifically, combining NLP semantic mathematics with relative frequency distributions—allows us to cut through the noise of generic job titles. It tells the story of how data work is no longer siloed in the tech sector, but is deeply integrated into Manufacturing, Finance, and Retail. Finally, by walking the audience through our SOC-to-SIC crosswalk and our Alpha ($\alpha$) markup methodology, we show how raw text data can be translated into a compelling macroeconomic narrative: a concrete monetary valuation of the UK's hidden data economy.
